{{Infobox Buddha
| 名 = Shakyamuni Tathagata (釈迦如来)
| 梵名 = शाक्यमुनि
| 別名 = Shakyamuni Buddha<br/>Shakyamuni Tathagata<br/>Shakyamuni World Honored One<br/>Shakyamuni<br/>Muni<br/>Shakya World Honored One
| 種字 = [[File:Bhah.svg|25px]] Bak
| 真言・陀羅尼 = Nōmaku Sanmanda Bodanan Bak
| 画像 = [[File:Shaka Muroji Mirokudo.jpg|250px]]
| 説明文 = {{ill|National Treasure|ja|国宝|qq=draft}} wooden seated Shakyamuni Tathagata statue ({{ill|Muroji Temple|ja|室生寺|qq=draft}})
| 経典 = {{ill|Lotus Sutra|ja|法華経|qq=draft}}
| 信仰 = {{ill|Theravada Buddhism|ja|上座部仏教|qq=draft}}<br/>{{ill|Mahayana Buddhism|ja|大乗仏教|qq=draft}}
| 浄土 = {{ill|Vulture Peak|ja|霊鷲山|qq=draft}} Pure Land
| See Also = {{ill|Prabhutaratna Buddha|ja|多宝如来|qq=draft}}<br/>{{ill|Manjushri|ja|文殊菩薩|qq=draft}}<br/>{{ill|Samantabhadra|ja|普賢菩薩|qq=draft}}
}}
'''Shakyamuni Tathagata''' (釈迦如来, Shaka Nyorai) refers to the historical [[Buddha]] and founder of [[Buddhism]], [[Shakyamuni]] (Gautama Siddhartha, Siddhattha Gotama, Siddhartha Gautama, 瞿曇悉達多), in his aspect as a Tathagata. He is also called Shakyamuni Buddha, Shakyamuni World Honored One, and simply Shakyamuni.

== Shakyamuni Tathagata in Buddhist History ==

=== Theravada Buddhism ===
In {{ill|Theravada Buddhism|ja|上座部仏教|qq=draft}}, Shakyamuni Tathagata is regarded as a historical and living Buddha, a manifestation distinct from the conceptualized [[Dharmakaya]].<ref>[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E7%90%86%E4%BB%8F%E6%80%A7-658308 ‘理仏性’ - Kotobank]</ref>

=== Mahayana Buddhism ===
In {{ill|Mahayana Buddhism|ja|大乗仏教|qq=draft}}, Shakyamuni is seen as an emanation of the [[Dharmakaya]] Buddha, teaching the Dharma in the form of a [[Nirmanakaya]] or [[Sambhogakaya]].

== Shakyamuni Tathagata's Past Lives ==
; Sumedha (from ‘{{ill|Buddhavamsa|ja|仏種生経|qq=draft}}’ and ‘{{ill|Jataka tales|ja|ジャータカ|qq=draft}}’)
: A sage under {{ill|Dipankara Buddha|ja|燃燈仏|qq=draft}}, prophesied to become a Buddha in the future.
; Jyotipala Bodhisattva (‘{{ill|Lalitavistara Sutra|ja|方広大荘厳経|qq=draft}}’)
: Sumedha's reincarnation in the {{ill|Tusita Heaven|ja|兜率天|qq=draft}}, considered a previous incarnation of Shakyamuni.
; Nagabhadra (‘{{ill|Avalokitesvara Sutra|ja|観世音菩薩往生浄土本縁経|qq=draft}}’)
: A Brahmin priest whose children became {{ill|Avalokiteshvara|ja|観音菩薩|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Mahasthamaprapta|ja|勢至菩薩|qq=draft}}.

== Shakyamuni Tathagata as Depicted in Statues ==
{{For2|Shakyamuni reclining statues|涅槃仏}}
[[File:Siddham Bija Shaka.jpg|thumb|Shakyamuni Tathagata represented by the [[Siddham]] script seed syllable]]
Statues of Shakyamuni have been created throughout regions influenced by [[Buddhism]] since its origin in [[India]]. Depictions often narrate his life through artistic interpretations of various scenes, such as his birth, asceticism, enlightenment, teaching, and parinirvana.

In Japan, Shakyamuni is often depicted in seated teaching postures (Dharmachakra Mudra), signifying his role in spreading the Dharma. Common examples include statues from {{ill|Horyuji Temple|ja|法隆寺|qq=draft}}'s Golden Hall, {{ill|Kanimanji Temple|ja|蟹満寺|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Muroji Temple|ja|室生寺|qq=draft}}. 

=== Notable Statues ===
; National Treasures
* {{ill|Bronze Seated Shakyamuni Tathagata|ja|蟹満寺#文化財|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Kanimanji Temple|ja|蟹満寺|qq=draft}}, Kyoto)
* {{ill|Wooden Standing Shakyamuni Tathagata|ja|清凉寺#木造釈迦如来立像|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Seiryoji Temple|ja|清凉寺|qq=draft}}, Kyoto)
* {{ill|Reclining Shakyamuni|ja|涅槃像|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Horyuji Temple Five-Story Pagoda|ja|法隆寺五重塔|qq=draft}})
* {{ill|Bronze Birth Shakyamuni and Ritual Bowl|ja|東大寺の仏像#銅造誕生釈迦仏立像及び灌仏盤|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Todaiji Temple|ja|東大寺|qq=draft}}, Nara)

== Relic Veneration ==
Japan houses relics of Shakyamuni in temples like {{ill|Sensoji Temple|ja|浅草寺|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Dojoji Temple|ja|道成寺|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kakuozan Nittai-ji|ja|覚王山日泰寺|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Bodh Gaya Temple|ja|釈迦山大菩提寺|qq=draft}}.

== Shakyamuni in Fiction ==
* {{ill|Journey to the West|ja|西遊記|qq=draft}}: Guides {{ill|Tang Sanzang|ja|三蔵法師|qq=draft}} and disciplines {{ill|Sun Wukong|ja|孫悟空|qq=draft}}.
* "The Spider's Thread" by {{ill|Ryunosuke Akutagawa|ja|芥川龍之介|qq=draft}}: Shakyamuni grants redemption to the sinner Kandata.

== Related Concepts ==
* {{ill|Shakyamuni Trinity|ja|釈迦三尊|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Triple Gem|ja|三宝尊|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Buddhist Relics|ja|仏舎利|1=Śarīra|2=ja|3=仏舎利|4=de|5=Sarira|6=fr|7=Śarīra|1=Śarīra|qq=draft}}

